Exp no:02
 
 AIM:
To write a program in C language using Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) concepts such as encapsulation and data abstraction to store and display student information.

 ALGORITHM:

Start the program.

Define a structure Student with the following members:

Roll number (int)

Name (char[50])

Marks (float)

Function pointers for input and display.

Define two functions:

inputStudent() to read student details.

displayStudent() to print student details.

Define a constructor function newStudent() to:

Allocate memory for a new Student.

Initialize data and assign function pointers.

In the main() function:

Create a Student object using newStudent().

Call its input() method to enter data.

Call its display() method to display data.

Free the dynamically allocated memory.

Stop the program.

ðŸ’» PROGRAM
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

typedef struct {
    int rollNo;
    char name[50];
    float marks;

    void (*input)(struct Student *self);
    void (*display)(struct Student *self);
} Student;

void inputStudent(Student *self) {
    printf("Enter Roll Number: ");
    scanf("%d", &self->rollNo);
    getchar(); 
    printf("Enter Name: ");
    fgets(self->name, sizeof(self->name), stdin);
    self->name[strcspn(self->name, "\n")] = '\0';
    printf("Enter Marks: ");
    scanf("%f", &self->marks);
}

void displayStudent(Student *self) {
    printf("\n--- Student Information ---\n");
    printf("Roll No : %d\n", self->rollNo);
    printf("Name    : %s\n", self->name);
    printf("Marks   : %.2f\n", self->marks);
}

Student *newStudent() {
    Student *s = (Student *)malloc(sizeof(Student));
    s->rollNo = 0;
    strcpy(s->name, "");
    s->marks = 0.0f;
    s->input = inputStudent;
    s->display = displayStudent;
    return s;
}

int main() {
    Student *s1 = newStudent();
    s1->input(s1);
    s1->display(s1);
    free(s1);
    return 0;
}

INPUT::
Enter Roll Number: 101
Enter Name: Alice
Enter Marks: 89.5

output:
Roll No : 101
Name    : Alice
Marks   : 89.50

RESULT:
The program successfully demonstrates how OOP concepts can be simulated in C using structures, function pointers, and modular programming.
It accepts and displays student information in an organized manner.
